segments.text: Testing, testing.
Testing, testing.
Still testing.
Still testing.
We're testing a second time.
Testing, testing.
Testing.
Testing.
This is October the 4th.
We're in Evans Library, and I have the honor and pleasure of chatting with Dr. Susan Wynne about her A&M first, her undergraduate student days.
To introduce yourself to anyone who might listen or read, give a biographical summary sketch before you got to A&M.
Before I got to A&M.
Family, where you grew up, what did Mom and Dad do,
I was born into a TCU family, multi-generations.
Several generations lived in Fort Worth.
We grew up also in the Disciples of Christ Church, which was affiliated with TCU.
So it was a very strong network.
My older sister went to TCU.
We moved to Houston, though, the week before I started kindergarten, so I went all the way through the Houston Independent School District.
Poe Elementary, the Edgar Allan Poe Ravens.
I always thought that was a great name.
The Sidney Lanier Purple Pups and the Mirabeau B. Lamar Redskins.
My father, Matt Rudd, was president of the TCU Alumni Association in 1969.
He was a salesman of everything from...
He sold Colonel Sanders paper boxes in Kentucky back in the 50s and then went on to selling offshore drilling rigs in the oil heydays of Houston in the 60s and 70s.
Mom went to TCU as well and was president of the TCU Women's Club sometime in the 60s.
And she...
worked as an executive secretary, probably could have done a lot more than she did, but that's another story.
She was a good mom.

And I was always a straight-A student and loved being active, loved music, just wanted to do everything, and was valedictorian in my senior class at Lamar, even though in those days in the early 70s, they said that every kid who got a 4.0

was number one so there ended up being 13 of us and only later when one of my buddies broke into the principal's office to see if he was really the number one number one he found out that I was really the number one number one and I never really got the proper recognition for that and I've always kind of resented it but at least I know it was me.
In my junior, well, I guess it was my senior year, maybe into my junior year, I never thought I'd go anyplace but TCU.
That was just destiny.
And grandparents still lived in Fort Worth, and we went back up there all the time, active in church youth activities, which often centered around TCU.
And my chemistry teacher in high school said, if you got a big scholarship to A&M, would you go?
And I thought he'd lost his mind.
I just thought he had lost his mind, but I was intrigued.
And I started getting recruited by the President's Endowed Scholar Program in its early days.
And a friend of my sister's, I can't believe, I can't remember his last name, John, he'll come to me, had been a very bright, fun guy, and he had gotten a President's Scholarship to A&M.
And so that
helped with the validity of the uh... suggestion but in those days the cool kids didn't go to A&M and the smart kids didn't go to A&M and the country kids went to A&M and so I
just kind of toyed with the idea, but I said, well, listen, you know, come on up to campus, we'll show you around and give you the tour, and I just, I fell in love.
I also had a chance to be a delegate to SCONA when I was in high school, and so spent a couple days on campus then and fell in love then, and so between having gone to SCONA and
And that recruitment trip, I applied for the scholarship, got it.
I'll never forget.
Of course, I was a little concerned about how my family would react to the possibility of me going to A&M.
And Daddy worked out of the house, and he was such a character.
And the day that the letter came from A&M telling me that I'd been awarded the President's Scholarship, he got home first and got that letter.
And there's still
debate in our family as to whether or not he had steamed it open first or not.
We really don't know.
But he got a string and hung that string down in the middle of the kitchen so that that letter was right at eye level when I walked in the back door from school that day.
And so this was like September, October of my senior year.
So very early.
We didn't have early admissions back then.
So by...
Halloween, probably, of my senior year in high school, I was admitted.
I had my ID number.
I was on the list for the dorm.
I mean, everything was done.
It was just amazing.
And so I didn't even hear, I went ahead and applied to TCU.
Of course, didn't hear from them until spring.
Went to the TCU college thing that they had at the Shamrock Hotel, you know, back then.
And I just thought, oh my gosh, what am I going to do?
And I went ahead and applied for a Chancellor's Scholarship, which was an even more prestigious scholarship at TCU than the President's Endowed Scholarship was.
Got it, and turned it down.
Because I had fallen in love with A&M.
And I had already heard some, you know, the inklings about the medical school.
And I knew I wanted, I even knew I wanted to be an allergist when I was in high school.
Knew I wanted to go into medicine.
And nobody in my family had been in medicine.
Daddy had an old trainer's Bible when he played high school football at Birdville High in Fort Worth.
And I read that thing from cover to cover.
It just fascinated me.
And then I read the Reader's Digest Home Medical Guide from cover to cover.
I just could not get enough of it.
And everybody in my family thought I'd lost my mind.
And so the prospect of being able to get into medical school after two years of college was very appealing to me.
And I'd grown up in Houston.
I didn't want any part of the medical center.
It was too big and too... That was my backyard.
I grew up with all the kids whose parents were doctors over there, and that didn't seem very glamorous to me at all.
You know, it's funny, the perspectives we had.
When you came up, say, for SCONA or any other pre-enrollment visits, what was it that impressed you about A&M?
the mood on campus.
I'd spent a lot of time on the TCU campus.
I'd spent a lot of time on the Rice campus because I grew up about a mile north of Rice University and that's where I rode my bike and
I had family friends that had gone there and learned how to drive in the Rice Stadium parking lot.
And the mood on campus, the looks on the faces of the students, just the gestalt of the whole experience was entirely different.
And that was apparent to me even at those brief time periods that I had visited there.
You know, of course, this was 1973, tail end of the Vietnam era.
You know, protests going on in other campuses.
You know, my sister's friends having draft numbers.
She was two and a half, three years older in school, two and a half years in age than I was.
And the angst that I saw on the other campuses was not here.
And I liked that.
Did you go to fish camp?
Nope.

didn't know I don't know I had a busy summer scheduled and I don't really think that I realized how important it was and it may have conflicted with some church stuff that I was doing so so I didn't go all right now this is the fall of 74 when you come up to enroll
who brought you and what did you bring?
All the stuff.
Oh, Lord.
Daddy brought me, and I remember we kind of had our signals crossed, and I thought I had a couple more days at home than I did, and it was really at the last minute.
It was like, oh, my God, I've got to register this afternoon.
And I tearfully told my best friend goodbye on the phone, and Daddy threw me in the car, and we went.
Mom didn't go.
I think Sally had already gone back to TCU for her senior year.
And I remember I had a cool stereo that I had bought with money that I had earned working the year before at a stereo store.
I just gave my paycheck back and bought a nice stereo.
And I had a bunch of clothes.
I remember I had met my roommate at orientation.
We had been roommates just by potluck at orientation.
Decided we got along pretty well.
So Stephanie Forrest from San Antonio.
And so we thought we were really cool because we had matching bedspreads.
We just thought we were pretty hot.
But we didn't have rugs.
We didn't have, I think, more what we didn't have in terms of more than what we had.
We didn't have a TV.
We didn't have, you know, certainly.
Didn't have a microwave.
Didn't have a microwave.
Did have a little refrigerator.
Did get the little refrigerator.
And this was in what dorm?
Kruger.
Kruger.
And yours truly was the M.C.
at the Grand Open.
Oh, gosh.
It was, oh, because that was just the cool place to live in the Commons.
Because that was before Mosier and Esten had opened.
It was just Kruger and Dunn.
What were they, generally describe the people who lived in Kruger Dunn?
What were they, where were they from?
What were they like?
What were they?
In general, the Kruger Dunn kids were the big city, middle class kids like me.
And there were some of the kids from the smaller towns.
But in general, the women that lived in Kruger with me that I became, and I'm still very, very close to, that group of girls that lived together that first year.
They still come meet me for the first football game every year.
We're very close.
They were from big high schools in San Antonio and Arlington, and they were business majors and education majors.
Were they all, like you, not an Aggie family?
Many of them were not Aggie families.
Some were.
Some were, some weren't.
A lot of women, their dads had gone to A&M.
And you knew when you, before you got here,
what your career goal was and what your major was.
And that was your choice.
Was there anyone who deserves credit now for having affected that career goal for you?
Well, I think the allergists that were my doctors at McGovern Allergy Clinic were very encouraging.
My family
Daddy was very proud of me, but I was Daddy's little princess, and pretty much anything I did, Daddy thought was just wonderful.
And if his little girl wanted to be a doctor, he just thought that was great.
I think Mother thought I had lost my mind.
Why would you want to work that hard?
We know that you're smarter than anybody in the family, but why would you want to work so hard?
But it was very, you know, my chemistry teacher in high school encouraged me.
Some church people encouraged me.
But it was really, it was a very deep internal passion for me.
You're confirming one thing we learned in the 60s doing that aspirations report.
We were trying to find out who, what, how most affects a young person's choice of where to go to college.
We found out that as often as not, parents were negative that the kids would rebel.
But the most central one was that youngster's favorite teacher, advisor, counselor, particularly related to what their major might be.
That is, your English teacher's advice would not have been nearly as important as your chemistry teacher's.
And so you're confirming that.
Fascinating.
All right.
Did you have to go through registration?
Yes.
Yes.
How did you register?
Stand in line?
Yep.
Standing in line.
And I can remember...
I took the advanced placement tests.
Back then, you didn't have courses.
It was just if you wanted to take the test to place that, you could.
You actually got grades.
I placed out of Spanish, all my Spanish, which now I really regret not having taken any.
So I thought, cool, Spanish is done.
I can cross that one off the list.
placed out of chemistry, but it would have been with a C, out of freshman chemistry.
And I remember the dean of the College of Science, John Beckham, what was his name?
Well, he was the associate dean.
Okay.
He had a deep throat.
I was talking to him.
I remember sitting at a table.
I was looking at my transcript.
I was signing up for freshman chemistry, or seeing if I could place out of freshman chemistry and just go on to organic or something.
And he said, you know, you're pre-med.
You may not want to do that.
That may not be the best idea.
The seal will go on your transcript.
Regular freshman chemistry is just going to bore you to tears.
Even though you're not a chemistry major, I want to put you in the chemistry for chemistry majors.
And of course, I was young and idealistic.
And I thought, oh, cool.
That's great.
Because I remember my sixth grade teacher telling me, if you have the opportunity to take an advanced class or an honors class or something, do it.
Always avail yourself of that opportunity.
And so I still had that mindset.
And so there were 30 kids in the classes compared to 300 in the big seminar classes.
I made an A the first semester.
But what I didn't realize is that they graded, it wasn't really even a curve.
The top 10 kids in the class got A's, the middle 10 kids in the class got B's, and the bottom 10 kids in the class got C's.
And so I may have made my first semester, but I made a C the second semester, even though I really didn't do that badly.
And it just blew my GPA.
And I've been mad at that man ever since for giving me that advice.
But...

When I took quantitative analysis my junior year, I just flew through it with A's because of that background that I had gotten in that freshman chemistry class, although it was kind of just my grade point average then.
Some other important courses that first semester that you remember?
Teachers, courses?
Well, I took the big freshman biology class.
Don't remember much about that at all, except it was big and boring.
English?
English.
Placed out of English.
Placed out of freshman English.
Math, history?
Math.
I took pre-calculus from a teaching assistant who I couldn't understand.
I took honors history.
I was in the honors program.
It didn't turn me on.
Didn't do real well in there.
It was, but boy, I sure enjoyed student government in Skona, and boy, I jumped into student activities feet first.
Now, how did, were you self-propelled there, or did somebody encourage you?

Oh, yeah, I was, I've been an inveterate joiner from day one, and so I was in, got involved in student, and all the gals I lived with, we all were executive aides for student government, got involved in Skona because I had been in Skona, and I had always played the piano in high school, and
auditioned for the Century Singers, but Bob made me the accompanist.
Of course, he was doing that in the scene.
Bob Boone.
Yeah, doing that in the scene, get up at the same time, made me an accompanist because he needed the piano player more than he needed another alto.
And so I spent every noon playing the piano for an hour in between my classes.
And I'll never forget my young
I almost had too much fun my freshman year.
It was probably about February my freshman year, and the Aggie players were going to do Godspell, and Godspell, I'd played all the way through high school, knew all the music, just loved it.
And a lot of the kids in the chorus who were auditioning for Godspell wanted me to play for their auditions.
I was like, okay, that's fine.
You know, it's like, I'm pretty bad, I don't have time to do this show, but, you know, I'll play for your audition, that'll be kind of fun, because I knew the music by heart.
And so I had played for two or three kids that had auditioned, and John Joy was the head of the theater department and Aggie Players back then.
What a character he was.
So this poor kid had just sung this mediocre audition solo off-key.
So John was like, okay, nice audition.
You, what's your name?
He points to me at the piano.
I'm like, Sue Rudd.
Sue, how do you spell that?
Fine, you're playing for the show.
And then goes on.
I'm like, no, no, wait, you don't understand.
You know this music.
I need you.
And so I was like, oh, okay.
So at one point in time, so I was the music director for Godspell.
So I taught all the singers all the music as well as playing with the band.
And so there were times at the end of my freshman year when I was playing the piano six hours a day in addition to trying to be a pre-med.
And just doing government and scone and all this other kind of stuff.
Describe during that year, describe your routine from getting up to going to bed at night
A typical day, what time did you get up and do what and where and when?
I don't think I had any 8 o'clock classes my freshman year.
I really don't remember.
I'd get up, because I always had to have breakfast, go down to the Commons for breakfast.
How did a young lady dress in that dining hall for breakfast?
We dressed.
We dressed.
I mean, you put your makeup on and you got dressed.
It was not unusual for us to wear dresses and pantyhose and heels to class or a cool pantsuit or something like that.
But you'd eat with your friends.
Your classes, by and large, were held where?
They were all over.
Biology would be in the biology building.
Chemistry was in the chemistry building.
History was either in Harrington or the history building.
I don't even remember.
It may have been the academic building.
So it was all over the place.
Fortunately, I didn't have to go down to Zachary, because at that point in time, that just seemed so far away.
And I'd have two or three classes in the morning.

I'd head over to the MSC at lunch and play piano for an hour, try to run back to the commons to grab a bite to eat before the lunch line closed, and then usually had some kind of lab in the afternoon, chemistry lab, biology lab, something like that.
We'd go till 5, get back to the dorm, grab a bite to eat.
And in the evenings, I always had some type of committee meeting, student senate, SCONA.
There was always something to do.
Where did you study?
Usually in my room, or in the study carrels.
I didn't come to the library very much.
Was it quiet?
Yeah, it really was.
It was pretty quiet.
Sometimes I'd go in the study carrels, because everybody was going off in so many different directions.
And we didn't have TVs and all this kind of stuff in our rooms.
So the rooms were really pretty quiet.
How did a new co-ed get introduced to Aggie traditions?
Particularly one whose background was purple and white.
Yes.
Basically going to, you know, meeting kids that had gone to fish camp.
Because a lot of the gals that I ran around with had gone to fish camp.
And it's, you know, when Silver Taps comes along,
you know, everything came to a screeching halt and everybody went to Silver Taps and the lights were out.
It was just, it was a herd mentality.
I hate to...
When you went to your first Silver Taps, what impression did it make?
It was, it was really an overwhelming experience for me.
I did not know the student who had been killed.
I was just amazed at how the mood
And the energy level on campus, just like somebody had flipped a switch all of a sudden.
And walking quietly towards the academic building, stunned by the power of the silence and the quiet among rowdy people who were all of a sudden quiet, solemn.
It was a very spiritual experience for me.
And then walking back to campus, I mean back to the dorm, and the whole rest of the night, people were quiet.
Let me add an editorial note for the typist here.
Somewhere about this time in the early 70s as dean of faculties, a group of students came to me to ask for advice regarding whether or not they should hold silver taps
for an undergraduate who lived off campus who had gotten killed in a car wreck after burglarizing a 7-Eleven store in Brenham.
Oh, wow.
And they were, should they or should they not?
As I recall, my response to them was to ask them a question, for whom do you hold silver taps?
for Aggies.
Was this an Aggie?
Was he enrolled or not?
He was enrolled.
I said, all right, I leave it to your judgment.
They held silver taps.
Wow.
Which I think was appropriate.
Yeah, I do too.
Who are we to judge?
Exactly.
Would I want them to have silver taps for me if I had gotten myself in a stupid situation like that?
Yeah.
All right.
What was it like to go to your first Aggie home football game?
as a student.
Oh, my gosh, it was just absolutely amazing.
Of course, hearing kids on campus talk about, you know, what football games were like, you know, seeing the excitement of the guys in the Corps, hearing the band practice.
Really, the first Midnight Yale practice was just absolutely incredible.
I don't really remember that much about it.
I know I didn't have a date, but just, I was like, how could you get all these people together?
at midnight on a Friday night.
And even though kids, of course, back then the drinking age was 18.
So, you know, everybody had been drinking and everybody had been partying and it was just absolutely wild.
But it was just an amazing experience.
It's kind of hard to describe.
Up at the first football game, I was like,
can I really stand up the whole game?
But back in those days, we wore dresses and heels and hoes to football games and stood on those damn bleachers for three hours in the heat and just didn't think a thing about it.
Now, was it socially okay for a young lady to go to a game without a date?
Well, yeah, because there were enough of us back then that we weren't really alone.
And it was less socially acceptable to not go to the game than it was to go without a date.
Since you weren't in the Corps and all that, was there any kind of Corps...
put-downs of you co-eds?
No, they loved it.
But it was the first year of W-1.
So it was the very first year that women were in the Corps.
And so there were a lot of negative attitudes directed towards them.
Gosh, those women had such a hard time.
I just am so amazed at their stick-to-itiveness and their stamina, having to endure what I know they must have endured.
I didn't know any of them very well.
As far as you recall, about how many were there in W-1?
Oh, I'm thinking 20 or 30.
That's what I thought.
Yeah.
Two dozen or so.
Yeah.
And hearing the guys in the Corps, very negative things.
Did you give any thought to being in the Corps yourself?
No, not for a minute.
I didn't want any part of that.
And so when you and your female, your co-ed colleagues, same class and so forth, you all didn't get anything said?
You don't remember things said behind your back as you walked down the hallway or anything?
All right.
Did, let's see, Midnight Y'all Practices, oh, Bonfire.
Bonfire.
What did you and your co-ed friends, what did, did y'all do anything regarding Bonfire?
Women didn't have anything to do with Bonfire back then.
And it was on the Duncan?
Yeah, yeah.
We, you know, watched it go up.
It was really a totally male activity.
And we all thought they were kind of nuts, but we admired what they were doing and thought it was really cool.
And just the, you know, and to me, a frosty clear November day will always be bonfire weather.
Hearing the guys go, it's bonfire weather, and their excitement about that.
And then...
I don't even remember if I went to Bonfire my freshman year.
I don't remember.
Because I went home for Thanksgiving and maybe I did.
Did you go to any out-of-town football games?
Yes.
Came home for
I guess it was a rice game.
Of course, you know, living a mile away from the campus, that was easy to come home for the weekend with a bunch of friends and go to the game.
So at your house you had a number of guests that weekend?
Yeah, yeah, and my poor parents had no idea what had hit them.
How did you, during that first fall, how did you communicate
with home?
Letters or phone calls?
Phone calls mostly, letters and phone calls.
And mom and dad, dad would call every once in a while and mom would, mom didn't call much, but it was so expensive to make a lot of phone calls.
And your cell phone didn't work very well then?
No, it really didn't.
Email wasn't running.
How did you, as you're beginning academically, how did you feel about the way your progress that first semester academically?
Were you doing pretty well?
I didn't do as well as I... Of course, I'd never made...
I made one B between eighth grade and my senior year in high school.
And made a couple of Bs.
And I may have even made a C on something that first semester because I played so much.
And I remember that was kind of a very rude awakening.
Because I knew that I had to keep my grades up if I wanted to get into medical school.
And if I wanted to keep my scholarship, I had to have over...
I think I had to have over a 3.0 to keep my president's scholarship.
It may have been a 3.2.
So it was a, you know, you had to keep it together.
Who did you turn to for advice?
Nobody.
No, you didn't have?
No.
Let me turn back on.
At the end of that first semester, you didn't do quite as well as you had hoped, and did that change anything in your...
I started doubting...
whether or not I could really get into medical school.
And by the end of the second semester, when I really didn't do much better, I actually changed my major from pre-med to pre-pharmacy.
I just thought, I'm not too sure I can cut this.
And so then, so came back my sophomore year as a pre-pharmacy major, but worked at
the allergy clinic where the allergist had been mentors to me as a summer job.
Oh, very good.
After your freshman year.
Yes.
Oh, splendid.
And so worked there full-time.
And those guys had known me since I was five years old because I had bad allergies and asthma as a child.
And saw everything.
Saw what the nurse...
I never...
toyed with nursing.
I never wanted to do that, but I thought, well, med tech, pharmacy, something medically related, because I really liked the chemistry aspects of it.
And they let me do everything.
I did everything from filing charts to putting patients in the room until by the end of the summer, I knew how to give allergy shots and skin testing, and they taught me everything.
It was just wonderful.
And really, by the end of that sometime,
At the end of that summer, sometime during my sophomore year, I realized, I like what the doctors do.
That's what I want to do.
I don't want to do what any of these other people do.
So I got back on track again sometime, I believe, during my sophomore year.
I was taking more of a traditional sophomore pre-med curriculum, regular organic chemistry, Shakespeare, to finish my English requirements.
What else?
I guess Chordate Anatomy is what sophomores took then.
Classic old guy that taught Chordate.
He taught Chordate forever.
I don't remember his name, but he was amazing.
The labs with those classes, probably, oh gosh, I don't remember what else I took.
No, I took that during summer school.
Did you have any teachers that really made an
deep impression on you.
No.
Really?
And it's, and I never, I was so damn independent and so stubborn and I think probably a little intimidated too.
I never.
